# Slide Composition

## Structure

- One idea per slide. If a slide needs "and also," split it.
- 30pt minimum font for prose. 20pt minimum for code.
- Code blocks: 5-10 lines max with the key line visually distinct. Longer code belongs in a live demo, not a slide.
- Prefer diagrams, comparisons, and decision matrices over bullet lists. If a slide has more than 4 bullets, restructure it.
- Use `#pause` for progressive disclosure: reveal one point at a time on comparison tables, step-by-step algorithms, and "predict then reveal" sequences.
- Use `#focus-slide[...]` for the opening question of each session and for key "one sentence to remember" moments.

## Rhythm

- Target 30-45 slides per 90-minute session. Each slide should be on screen for 2-3 minutes, not 10.
- No slide should stay visible for more than 5 minutes. If it does, the content should be split or moved to a live demo.
- Place demo/exercise breaks every 15-20 minutes to reset attention.

## Text

- Slides complement speech. They show what's hard to say (diagrams, code, data). The instructor says what's hard to show (intuition, motivation, connections).
- Never put full sentences that will be read aloud verbatim. The slide and the instructor should not say the same thing.
- Use consistent terminology across all sessions. If a concept has synonyms, pick one and flag alternatives explicitly when first introduced.

## Metropolis Theme Conventions

- Keep the progress bar enabled (default).
- Session title in `config-info.title`, day identifier in `config-info.institution` (used as footer).
- Level-2 headings (`==`) create content slides. Do not use level-1 headings (`=`) within a session file — those create section dividers and belong only if the session has distinct multi-topic arcs.
